\"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime - Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy in the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometry will rely on new techniques, which will allow new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
\"For example, some people who work concrete have very low fingers and their fingerprints are illegible,\" notes Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand, involves a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - we cannot capture this data at their disposal - and a drawback: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been carried out for some 20 years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the computing capacity of computers needed for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a face or iris in motion.
\"Today, we are conducting research on the recognition of voice or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a silent environment,\" says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
\"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data - confirms Sophie Vokiet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometry are divided into two groups: identification (recognition of one person from another) and authentication (to ensure that the person is the one she claims to be).
The identification was so far concerned the issue of identity papers: the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all the citizens already numbered.
This makes it possible to ensure that someone does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus proposes the recognition of VIP at the entrance to a hotel or store.
\"We are collecting images of surveillance cameras and comparing them to the photos of celebrities that are freely circulating on the Internet,\" says Dany Nassif, in charge of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a picture of a quidam who tails in a store, follow its progression thanks to facial recognition and calculate waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control was added.
\"A biometric pointer avoids the match that points for another\" justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing its card and placing its hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the stamp of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with large distribution banks and presses: when paying in store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
Experimentation is planned for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tips to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometry attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash 30 seconds less, it’s good,” explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer custom options.
And, finally, ensure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
-The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it - names Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy specialists, they, continue to worry.
“The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance - Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada predicts.
