Scientists have just highlighted the way a dog's tail movements are related to its mood.
Previous studies revealed that happy dogs moved their tail further to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: \"Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.\"
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as well as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching films that included other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: \"We presented to dogs films where other dogs were included - either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factor - and we were able to trafic the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or to the right.\"
When the animals saw a dog without expression move the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deflecting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs would communicate deliberately with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: \"If you meet several times with other dogs and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience.\"
Researchers indicate that the results could enable owners, veterinarians and tenants to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs were turning their heads to the left when they were looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: \"The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail moved to the left rather than to the right, rather than to become anxious - the opposite of what is in the Italian study.\"
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or robots dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
