He walks in the mud, jungle and crosses rivers to offer free medical assistance
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free health care in the villages of Cameroon
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend most of their weekends seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country, only 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, for the election \"Heros CNN of the year\".
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and went to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that he was going to carry the consequences for the rest of his life.
\"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,\" said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr.Bwelle spent years with his father in crowded clinics and hospitals to get any treatment he could get.
\"It's not easy,\" says Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five o'clock, ride to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 physician for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health expenditures are in the private sector.
\"The only problem they have is poverty,\" Dr. Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed more than 700 surgical acts for free last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which goes to rural areas during the weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they settle in vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and crossing difficult terrains to go to villages that need the most help.
Chance doesn't follow them all the time.
They have often had to push vehicles to cross muddy rivers or slopes.
But when they arrive, they are received in heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle - with his big smile and energy overflowing - is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team starts receiving hundreds of patients.
\"We receive 500 people every visit,\" said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this travelling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive beets, a pair of glasses collected or a free birth certificate - a necessary document to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the practical team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, a city hall or a house; after the intervention, the patient gets up and goes to the waking room to leave his place for the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the first hours of Sunday morning.
It's a rising pace, but villagers' musicians usually help the team to stay motivated.
\"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work,\" said Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of her work.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical acts free of charge last year, and he knows that their presence can make a difference for those to whom they come to help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to care for a hernia would allow him to work again.
\"This will change my future and that of my family,\" said the man.
In addition to having this hospital live and work as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works in private medical offices around Yaoundé at night.
It is this second job, he explains, which funds 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
\"I don't know when he's sleeping,\" said Katie O'Malley, a second year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteering in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association in order to conduct these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr.Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity to learn on the ground that they do not have at home.
\"We were able to participate in operations to help spray the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,\" said Ms. O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a medical student in the second year.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
\"He's a hero, there's no doubt,\" said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not about to go out.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a challenge.
Helping others to live happily by keeping the promise he has made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
\"I am so happy when I do this work,\" said Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
To make people laugh and to relieve pain are the reasons why I want to do this.
